Opa-locka: A City Steeped in Arabian Nights Fantasy

Opa-locka, Florida: Where Moorish Dreams Come to Life

Opa-locka, a city in Miami-Dade County, Florida, is a place where the fantastical world of the Arabian Nights has been brought to life. Founded in 1926 by aviation pioneer Glenn Curtiss, this unique community was inspired by the exotic splendor of the One Thousand and One Nights tales.

Architectural Marvels: Moorish Revival Wonders

The city's most striking feature is its impressive collection of Moorish Revival architecture, one of the largest in the Western Hemisphere. Designed by architect Bernhardt E. Muller, the buildings feature iconic elements like onion-shaped domes, minarets, Saracenic arches, and intricate mosaic tiles. [Opa-locka Thematic Resource Area](/Opa-locka_Thematic_Resource_Area), a group of 20 historic Moorish-style structures, is listed on the National Register of Historic Places.

Streets bear names like [Sharazad](/Sharazad) Boulevard, [Sinbad](/Sinbad) Avenue, and [Ali Baba](/Ali_Baba) Avenue, transporting visitors to a bygone era of Arabian fantasy. The Opa-locka train station, once billed as the "grand Vizier of the Sheikdom of Opa-locka," welcomed passengers arriving on the famous [Orange Blossom Special](/Orange_Blossom_Special_(train)) train.

A City of Contrasts: From Prosperity to Decline

Opa-locka experienced a period of growth and prosperity in its early years, with the founding of a hotel, zoo, golf course, and other amenities. However, the [Great Miami hurricane](/1926_Miami_hurricane) of 1926 and the end of the Florida land boom slowed the city's development.

In the 1930s, the [U.S. Navy](/U.S._Navy) opened a base at the Opa-locka Airport, contributing to the city's growth. But the base's closure in the 1950s led to a decline in Opa-locka's fortunes.

Racial Transition and Challenges

The city underwent a significant demographic shift in the 1980s, transitioning from a majority white population to a majority African American one. Opa-locka was seen as a pioneer in black empowerment in northern [Dade County](/Miami-Dade_County), where neighboring cities were also experiencing racial changes.

In the 2000s and 2010s, Opa-locka faced financial troubles and a federal corruption investigation, leading the state of Florida to declare a financial emergency in the city in 2016. The city's government and infrastructure have struggled with these challenges.

Preserving a Unique Heritage

Despite the city's ups and downs, Opa-locka remains a place of unique architectural and cultural heritage. The annual "Arabian Nights Fantasy" celebration continues to promote civic pride and community, while the city's Moorish-inspired buildings and streets stand as a testament to its extraordinary origins.

As Opa-locka navigates its future, preserving and celebrating its one-of-a-kind identity will be crucial. This city, born from the fantastical imagination of its founders, continues to captivate all who encounter its Moorish-tinged charms.

